<mujoco model="MyoHand_v0.1.7_env">
<!-- A structured grasp environment modeled on the MyoChallenge'24 myoMPL
    "Prosthesis Co-Manipulation" task (Table I / Fig. 2 of the paper the user
    supplied): start pillar, goal pillar, an object with full 6-DoF free
    state, and an observation/reward structure built around reach error and
    per-body touch categories, rather than the ad hoc single-purpose checks
    in myohand_exoglove_grasp.xml (kept untouched, on purpose, so the two
    environments can be compared side by side -- see grasp_env.py).

    SCOPE NOTE vs. the source paper: their task is bimanual (myoArm + MPL
    prosthetic) with a literal handover and object transport between two
    pillars. We only actuate the hand/thumb via the exoskeleton devices (no
    shoulder/elbow/wrist muscles are driven anywhere in this project), so
    there is no "reach the palm toward the object" or "carry it to the goal"
    phase available to us -- the object has to already be within the fingers'
    natural closing arc. No goal pillar/bimanual handover here (removed on
    request -- we're not doing bimanual manipulation); if the reach-phase
    controller gets built later, a goal can be reintroduced then.

    Object orientation CORRECTED per user: the 88mm dimension is vertical
    (Z), not 28mm -- the box stands on its narrow 72x28mm face, long axis up.
    This also changes the thumb-vs-finger contact geometry for the better:
    logged contact normals during closing showed the thumb pressing straight
    down onto the box's TOP face (normal ~(0,0,-1)) while the fingers pressed
    the SIDE face (normal ~(0,1,0)) -- ~90 deg apart, not opposing, because
    the box was too short (28mm) to give the thumb anything but the top to
    land on. Standing it up gives the thumb a tall side face to meet the
    fingers on instead. Y (72mm, the face the fingers were already pressing)
    is left unchanged; only X (was 88mm) and Z (was 28mm) swap. -->

    <include file="assets/myohand_assets.xml"/>
    <include file="../../myosuite/simhive/myo_sim/scene/myosuite_scene.xml"/>
    <compiler meshdir="../../myosuite/simhive/myo_sim" texturedir="../../myosuite/simhive/myo_sim"/>

    <worldbody>
        <include file="assets/myohand_body.xml"/>
        <!-- REVISED after visual failure: raising the object to 1.455 was
            wrong. Traced actual fingertip-mesh trajectories (thumbdist/
            2distph/3distph geom_xpos) through the full closing motion with
            no object present: the fingers curl DOWN and toward the wrist as
            they close, so a HIGHER object sits where the OPEN hand starts,
            not where the closed hand converges -- by the time the fingers
            reach that height they've already curled past it. The genuine
            convergence point (steady-state, fully closed) is thumb~
            (-0.11,-0.40,1.38), index~(-0.16,-0.46,1.34), middle~
            (-0.19,-0.46,1.34) -- centroid (-0.15,-0.44,1.35), matching
            (within ~1cm) the ORIGINAL myohand_exoglove_grasp.xml placement
            (-0.144,-0.458,1.352) that was already empirically verified to
            get genuine contact on all 8 devices. Reverted to that proven
            X/Y/Z rather than the guessed 1.455.

            Pillar rebuilt as a floor-to-object cylinder (matches the
            MyoAssist paper figure's pedestal, not a small plate floating in
            mid-air) -- also wide enough (12cm diameter) to fully support the
            object's 8.8x7.2cm footprint, since the old 6x6cm plate was
            SMALLER than the object and let it tip/rotate off-square (the
            "crooked" object the user saw). Floor is at z=-.4 (myosuite_scene
            "floor" geom). -->
        <body name="start_pillar" pos="-0.152 -0.478 0.469" mocap="true">
            <!-- box, not cylinder: box-vs-box is one of MuJoCo's analytic
                contact pairs; box-vs-cylinder fell back to a soft general
                convex path that let the object sink ~1.4cm into the pillar
                at rest (verified via contact dist ~ -0.0145 persisting
                indefinitely, not settling toward 0). Same robust shape the
            original working grasp_test.py support used, just full-height
            now for the floor-up pedestal look. Raised 3cm after live
            inspection of the large-pillar setup showed the object still
            started below the fingers' initial closing band, so the hand
            spent its first motion curling into empty space before it could
            make contact. Keeping the base on the floor means both the
            pillar center and its half-height increase by 1.5cm. -->
            <geom name="start_pillar_geom" type="box" size="0.06 0.06 0.869" friction="2.5 0.02 0.002" rgba="0.3 0.3 0.35 1"/>
        </body>
        <body name="grasp_object" pos="-0.152 -0.478 1.382">
            <!-- CENTER kept at the same proven height as the original flat
                box (1.352) rather than resting the new taller box's bottom
                on the old pillar height -- that would've raised the center
                3cm and stalled the weaker uncalibrated devices (D1-D3
                placeholder tau_max=0.03 Nm) well short of the object even
                after 30s of simulated closing. Same center, taller box means
                MORE of its surface (8.8cm span instead of 2.8cm) sits inside
                the fingers' natural closing arc, not less. Live tuning with
                the large pillar still showed a clear initial gap, so this
                env version lifts the object 3cm with the pillar to start the
                grasp inside the contact band instead of below it. A further
                small X/Y nudge toward the hand brings the object closer to
                the fingers' initial approach path without changing the basic
                pedestal layout. -->
            <freejoint/>
            <geom name="grasp_object_geom" type="box" size="0.014 0.036 0.044" mass="0.097" friction="2.5 0.02 0.002" rgba="0.8 0.2 0.2 1"/>
        </body>
    </worldbody>

</mujoco>
